Get the pacakges

The R package faraway has the dataset pima. Install and load the R package faraway. Extract pima data with data(pima) command.

Variables are:

pregnant (# of times) glucose (2 hours post tolerance test) age (years) diastolic (blood pressure) tricepts (skin fold thickness) insulin (2-hour insulin) bmi diabetes (pedigree-a number related to family history) test (diabetes signs +/-)

data("pima")

#Replace missing value of tricepts with mean
#

pima$triceps[0==pima$triceps] <- mean(pima$triceps[!0==pima$triceps],na.rm=TRUE)
pima$diastolic[0==pima$diastolic] <- mean(pima$diastolic[!0==pima$diastolic],na.rm=TRUE)
pima$bmi[0==pima$bmi] <- mean(pima$bmi[!0==pima$bmi],na.rm=TRUE)

Here is an example stepwise variable selection with AIC criterion.

  1. Perform stepwise selection using the stepAIC function in the MASS R package. Use all variables as predictors!
  2. Which model was selected as the best fit?
lmout <- lm(diastolic~age+diabetes+triceps+bmi,data=pima)
stepAIC(lmout,direction="both")

  1. Perform all possible regressions using regsubsets function in the leaps R package. Use all variables as predictors!
  2. What model has the best BIC (Bayesian Information Criterion)?
leaps<-regsubsets(diastolic~age+diabetes+triceps+bmi,data=pima,nbest=10)
# view results 
summary(leaps)

  1. Fit the model selected by BIC. What are the significant predictors?
fitBIC <- lm(formula = diastolic ~ age + bmi, data = pima)

fitBIC %>% gtsummary::tbl_regression()
Characteristic Beta 95% CI1 p-value
age 0.33 0.26, 0.39 <0.001
bmi 0.48 0.37, 0.59 <0.001
1 CI = Confidence Interval

  1. Look for influential observations whose removal effects the fit. We can compute the Cooks distance using the following commands.

  2. How is this an extreme observation?

cook <- cooks.distance(fitBIC)
plot(sort(cook), ylab="Cooks distances")

print(pima[cook==max(cook),],)
##     pregnant glucose diastolic triceps insulin bmi diabetes age test
## 126        1      88        30      42      99  55    0.496  26    1
